Confirmed Root Cause — Found in checkPhoneVerified()
Now we have the complete picture. Here’s exactly what’s failing and why.

The Exact Bug — checkPhoneVerified() in RemoteSupportServiceImpl

public String checkPhoneVerified(Person person, PersonVo personVo, RpEvent rpEvent, 
        RefOtpSupplier phoneSupplier, String serviceName, String origin) {

    boolean phoneVerified = false;
    
    // ← THIS IS THE PROBLEM
    RpPhoneVerification phoneVerification = 
        rpPhoneVerificationService.findPhoneVerificationByEventId(rpEvent.getEventId());
    
    if (phoneVerification != null) {
        phoneVerified = phoneVerification.isPhoneVerified();
        ...
    } else {
        return REASON_FAILED_PHONE_VERIFICATION;  // ← BC5 HITS THIS
    }


BC5 calls findPhoneVerificationByEventId() and gets null back — even though BC4 just wrote the record. Here’s the exact chain of why:

Complete Failure Sequence With Line References

1. VerifyPhone → BC4 (@Transactional begins)
   └── phoneVerificationService.sendPasscodeSuccessful(personVo, refOtpSupplier)
       └── Writes RpPhoneVerification row to DB
       └── Updates PersonProofingStatus → OTP_sent
   └── @Transactional commits ← record IS in DB

2. ConfirmPasscode → BC5 (round-robin, new @Transactional begins)
   └── rpEventDataService.findLatestEventByPersonId(personId)
       └── Gets the RpEvent ✅
   └── rpPhoneVerificationService.findPhoneVerificationByEventId(rpEvent.getEventId())
       └── ← Returns NULL or stale result ← BUG
   └── checkPhoneVerified() is called with this rpEvent
       └── Does ANOTHER query: findPhoneVerificationByEventId(rpEvent.getEventId())
           └── ← ALSO returns NULL
       └── hits: return REASON_FAILED_PHONE_VERIFICATION ← EARLY EXIT
   └── buildFailedPhoneVerificationResponseJSON() called
       └── responseMessage: "Phone: X was not verified for customer Y"
       └── phoneVerified: false, passcodeSent: false ← small 252-byte response


Why findPhoneVerificationByEventId() Returns Null on BC5
There are two compounding issues:
Issue A — RpEvent is fetched by BC5 with a stale eventId
Look at confirmPasscode() in RemoteProofingServiceImpl:

RpEvent rpEvent = rpEventDataService.findLatestEventByPersonId(personId);


This fetches the event correctly. But then checkPhoneVerified() does this internally:

RpPhoneVerification phoneVerification = 
    rpPhoneVerificationService.findPhoneVerificationByEventId(rpEvent.getEventId());


If the RpPhoneVerification record was written under a different eventId than what BC5’s findLatestEventByPersonId() returned, this query finds nothing. This can happen because verifyPhone() on BC4 may have created a new event via manageEventService.createEvent(personVo) and then written the phone verification under that new event’s ID — but BC5’s connection pool may be hitting a replica or getting a cached version of the event lookup.
Issue B — @Transactional Class-Level Isolation
Both services are annotated @Transactional at the class level:

// RemoteProofingServiceImpl.java
@Transactional
public class RemoteProofingServiceImpl ...

// RemoteSupportServiceImpl.java  
@Transactional
public class RemoteSupportServiceImpl ...


With default Spring @Transactional isolation (READ_COMMITTED), a transaction on BC5 can only see data committed before its transaction started. If BC5’s transaction opens its connection from the pool at the same millisecond BC4 is still committing verifyPhone(), BC5 will read a snapshot that doesn’t yet include the RpPhoneVerification row. The log timestamps confirm this — the calls are milliseconds apart.
Issue C — Double Query Problem
confirmPasscode() queries for rpPhoneVerification before calling checkPhoneVerified(), and then checkPhoneVerified() queries again independently:

// In confirmPasscode() — first query:
RpPhoneVerification rpPhoneVerification = 
    rpPhoneVerificationService.findPhoneVerificationByEventId(rpEvent.getEventId());
if (rpPhoneVerification != null) {
    personVo.setMobileNumber(rpPhoneVerification.getMobilePhoneNumber());
    // ← but phoneVerified status is NOT set on personVo here
}

// In checkPhoneVerified() — SECOND independent query:
RpPhoneVerification phoneVerification = 
    rpPhoneVerificationService.findPhoneVerificationByEventId(rpEvent.getEventId());
// ← This is a completely separate DB hit, not using the result from above


The result from the first query is never passed into checkPhoneVerified(). That method re-queries independently and is the one that fails.

The Fix — Minimal Code Change, Maximum Impact
Fix 1 — Pass rpPhoneVerification into checkPhoneVerified() (Primary Fix)
Change the signature of checkPhoneVerified() to accept the already-fetched record, eliminating the second query:
In RemoteSupportServiceImpl.java — modify checkPhoneVerified():

// CHANGE SIGNATURE — add rpPhoneVerification parameter
public String checkPhoneVerified(Person person, PersonVo personVo, RpEvent rpEvent, 
        RefOtpSupplier phoneSupplier, String serviceName, String origin,
        RpPhoneVerification rpPhoneVerification) {  // ← ADD THIS PARAM
    
    CustomLogger.enter(this.getClass());

    boolean phoneVerified = false;
    boolean phoneApproved = false;
    boolean phoneForReview = false;
    String phoneVerificationDecision = DECISION_FAIL;
    
    // REMOVE the internal DB query — use the passed-in record instead:
    // RpPhoneVerification phoneVerification = 
    //     rpPhoneVerificationService.findPhoneVerificationByEventId(rpEvent.getEventId()); ← DELETE

    if (rpPhoneVerification != null) {  // use the param directly
        phoneVerified = rpPhoneVerification.isPhoneVerified();
        phoneApproved = rpPhoneVerification.isEquifaxDITPhoneVerificationPassed() 
                || rpPhoneVerification.isExperianPhoneVerificationApproved();
        phoneForReview = rpPhoneVerification.isEquifaxDITPhoneVerificationForReview()
                || rpPhoneVerification.isExperianPhoneVerificationForReview();
        
        if (rpPhoneVerification.getTransactionKey() != null) {
            personVo.setTransactionId(rpPhoneVerification.getTransactionKey());
        }
    } else {
        return REASON_FAILED_PHONE_VERIFICATION;
    }
    
    // ... rest of method unchanged


In RemoteProofingServiceImpl.java — confirmPasscode(), update the call:

// EXISTING fetch — keep this:
RpPhoneVerification rpPhoneVerification = 
    rpPhoneVerificationService.findPhoneVerificationByEventId(rpEvent.getEventId());
if (rpPhoneVerification != null) {
    personVo.setMobileNumber(rpPhoneVerification.getMobilePhoneNumber());
}

// CHANGE THIS CALL — pass rpPhoneVerification in:
String reason = remoteSupportService.checkPhoneVerified(
    person, personVo, rpEvent, refOtpSupplier,
    RemoteSupportServiceImpl.CONFIRM_PASSCODE, origin,
    rpPhoneVerification);  // ← ADD THIS ARGUMENT


Do the same for requestPasscode() — it also calls checkPhoneVerified() and has the same pattern.

Fix 2 — Set phoneVerified on personVo After the First Query
As a defense-in-depth measure, after fetching rpPhoneVerification in confirmPasscode(), explicitly set the verification state on personVo so any code path that reads from personVo gets accurate data:

RpPhoneVerification rpPhoneVerification = 
    rpPhoneVerificationService.findPhoneVerificationByEventId(rpEvent.getEventId());

if (rpPhoneVerification != null) {
    personVo.setMobileNumber(rpPhoneVerification.getMobilePhoneNumber());
    // ADD THESE LINES:
    personVo.setTransactionId(rpPhoneVerification.getTransactionKey());
    // phoneVerified flag prevents checkPhoneVerified from failing blind
}


Fix 3 — Update requestPasscode() Too
requestPasscode() has the exact same pattern and will fail identically:

